3.3 Container Optimized OS 
Page 62 
3.3.1 Prefer using a container-optimized OS when possible 
(Manual) 
Profile Applicability: 
•  Level 2 
Description: 
A container-optimized OS is an operating system image that is designed for secure 
managed hosting of containers on compute instances. 
Use cases for container-optimized OSes might include: 
• 
Docker container or Kubernetes support with minimal setup. 
• 
A small-secure container footprint. 
• 
An OS that is tested, hardened and verified for running Kubernetes nodes in your 
compute instances. 
Rationale: 
Container-optimized OSes have a smaller footprint which will reduce the instance's 
potential attack surface. The container runtime is pre-installed and security settings like 
locked-down firewall is configured by default. Container-optimized images may also be 
configured to automatically update on a regular period in the background. 
Impact: 
A container-optimized OS may have limited or no support for package managers, 
execution of non-containerized applications, or ability to install third-party
